dates individually but lump them together.</small>\n\n==Results==\n===Early states===\n\n====Iowa====\nThe Iowa Democratic caucuses took place on February 3, 2020. The results of the 2020 Iowa caucuses have been certified; however, they have been challenged. As of February 29, 2020, that challenge is pending before the Democratic National Committee's Rules and Bylaws Committee.<ref name= \"certify\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/29/politics/iowa-democratic-caucuses-certified-results/index.html|title=Iowa Democratic Party certifies Buttigieg's Iowa lead amid Sanders challenge|work=CNN.com|last1=Levy|first1=Adam|last2=Merica|first2=Dan|date=March 1, 2020|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n{{excerpt|2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|fragment=IAresults}}\n\n====New Hampshire====\nThe New Hampshire Democratic primary took place on February 11, 2020.\n{{excerpt|2020 New Hampshire Democratic primary|fragment=NHresults}}\n\n====Nevada====\nThe Nevada Democratic caucus took place with early voting February 14 to 18, and was completed on February 22, 2020.\n{{excerpt|2020 Nevada Democratic caucuses|fragment=NVresults}}\n\n====South Carolina====\nThe South Carolina Democratic primary took place on February 29, 2020, three days prior to Super Tuesday.  \n{{excerpt|2020 South Carolina Democratic primary|fragment=SCresults}}\n\n===Super Tuesday===\n[[Super Tuesday]] took place on March 3, 2020.\n\n====Alabama====\n{{excerpt|2020 Alabama Democratic primary|fragment=ALresults}}\n\n====American Samoa====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 United States presidential caucuses in American Samoa}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 United States presidential caucuses in American Samoa|Results}}}}\n\n====Arkansas====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Arkansas Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Arkansas Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====California====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 California Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 California Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Colorado====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Colorado Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Colorado Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Maine====\n{{excerpt|2020 Maine Democratic primary|fragment=MEresults}}\n\n====Massachusetts====\n{{excerpt|2020 Massachusetts Democratic primary|fragment=MAresults}}\n\n====Minnesota====\n{{excerpt|2020 Minnesota Democratic primary|fragment=MNresults}}\n\n====North Carolina====\n{{excerpt|2020 North Carolina Democratic primary|fragment=NCresults}}\n\n====Oklahoma====\n{{excerpt|2020 Oklahoma Democratic primary|fragment=OKresults}}\n\n====Tennessee====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Tennessee Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Tennessee Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Texas====\n{{excerpt|2020 Texas Democratic primary|fragment=TXresults}}\n\n====Utah====\n{{excerpt|2020 Utah Democratic primary|fragment=UTresults}}\n\n====Vermont====\n{{excerpt|2020 Vermont Democratic primary|fragment=VTresults}}\n\n====Virginia====\n{{excerpt|2020 Virginia Democratic primary|fragment=VAresults}}\n\n===Mid/Late-March===\n====Democrats Abroad====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Democrats Abroad primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Democrats Abroad primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Idaho====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Idaho Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Idaho Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Michigan====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Michigan Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Michigan Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Mississippi====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Mississippi Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Mississippi Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Missouri====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Missouri Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Missouri Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====North Dakota====\n{{excerpt|2020 North Dakota Democratic caucuses|fragment=NDresults}}\n\n====Washington====\n{{excerpt|2020 Washington Democratic primary|fragment=WAresults}}\n\n====Northern Mariana Islands====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 United States presidential caucuses in the Northern Mariana Islands}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 United States presidential caucuses in the Northern Mariana Islands|Results}}}}\n\n====Arizona====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Arizona Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Arizona Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Florida====\n{{excerpt|2020 Florida Democratic primary|fragment=FLresults}}\n\n====Illinois====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Illinois Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Illinois Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n===April===\n====Wisconsin====\n{{transcluded section|source=2020 Wisconsin Democratic primary}}\n{{trim|{{#section-h:2020 Wisconsin Democratic primary|Results}}}}\n\n====Alaska====\n{{excerpt|2020 Alaska Democratic primary|fragment=AKresults}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"GP\">{{cite web|title=Nevada Democratic Delegation 2020|url=https://www.thegreenpapers.com/P20/NV-D|publisher=The Green Papers|date=March 31, 2019|accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref> <!-- [[2020 Nevada Democratic caucuses#Procedure]] -->\n}}\n{{2020 Democratic primaries}}\n\n[[Category:2020 United States Democratic presidential primaries]]\n|}\n", "name_user": "Arglebargle79", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther candidates", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Results_of_the_2020_Democratic_Party_presidential_primaries"}
{"title_page": "Book Off", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Book Off (\u30d6\u30c3\u30af\u30aa\u30d5\u30b3\u30fc\u30dd\u30ec\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3)\n| logo             = Bookoff Corporation Logo.svg\n| type             = [[Bookstore]]\n| genre            = \n| foundation       = 1991\n| founder          = \n| location_city    = [[Sagamihara, Kanagawa]]\n| location_country = [[Japan]]\n| location         = \n| locations        = \n| area_served      = Worldwide\n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Retail]]\n| products         = Second-hand [[book]]s, [[magazine]]s, [[manga]], [[CD]]s, [[DVD]]s, [[video game]]s, [[video game console]]s, [[mobile phone]]s and [[portable media player]]s\n| services         = \n| market cap       = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = \n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n[[File:Book off.jpg|thumb|Book OFF at Higashiyama, Nara]]\n[[File:Book Off Shibuya.jpg|200px|right|Book Off in the middle of [[Shibuya]]]]\n{{nihongo|'''Book Off'''|\u30d6\u30c3\u30af\u30aa\u30d5\u30b3\u30fc\u30dd\u30ec\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3|Bukku Ofu K\u014dpor\u0113shon}} ({{tyo|3313}}) is [[Japan]]'s largest chain of [[Used goods|used]] [[bookstore]]s. Founded in August 1991, the company has had explosive success, expanding to 866 stores throughout Japan and eight overseas locations (as of August 2006). In addition to books, its chains also sell [[manga]], [[CD]]s, [[DVD]]s, [[video game]]s, and even used [[video game consoles]], [[mobile phone]]s and [[portable media player]]s. The stores are distinguished by their large surface area, cleanliness and bright illumination.\n\n== Operations ==\n\nAs stores are larger it is easier for shoppers to find what they are looking for. Browsing is encouraged, shown with a typical scene of high-school students who read through entire series of [[manga]] standing quietly in the aisles. Another innovation cited for its success is the practice of shaving the edges off the pages of books using a special machine in order to make them appear newer.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | title =Screen savers\n  | newspaper =The Economist\n  | pages =\n  | year =\n  | date =May 24, 2007\n  | url =http://www.economist.com/business/displaystory.cfm?story_id=9231860}}</ref> By offering a wide selection of books that appear like new at reduced prices, Book Off has aggressively targeted conventional bookstore chains, which since 1953<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WSoj5nVrpR0C&pg=PA452|page=452|title=Handbook of Oriental Studies. Section 5 Japan, Modern Japanese Society|isbn=90-04-10516-6|author=J. Kreiner|author2=U. Mvhwald|author3=H. D. Vlschleger|year=2004}}</ref> have been unable to discount new and near-new books and other media due to government regulations which enable a publisher's cartel.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EizYm46Kv_AC&pg=PA390|title=Global Strategy|author=Mike W. Peng|year=2008|isbn=0-324-59099-7|pages=390\u2013393}}</ref>\n\nBook Off is frequently cited as a rare example of a corporation that was able to grow during the so-called \"lost decade\" of [[economic stagnation]] that followed the collapse of the [[Japanese asset price bubble]], through its use of innovative business strategies that are covered in the Japanese business press. It expanded from merely used books to used second-hand merchandise through its Hard Off stores and to the video rental market through Tsutaya.\n\n==International stores==\n\nBook Off also operates several stores in [[United States]], two in [[Seoul]] and two in [[Paris]]<ref>[https://lingonbook.fr/nos-boutiques-bookoff/ Nos Boutiques BOOKOFF]</ref>. In 2012, it closed its only Canadian store in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]. In the USA, there is one store in [[New York (state)|New York]], seven stores in [[California]], and two stores in [[Hawaii]].\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nImage:Book Off Manga.jpg|Thousands of manga volumes at Book Off\nImage:Book-Off! Op\u00e9ra Paris.jpg|Book-Off! store near Op\u00e9ra in [[Paris]]\nImage:Book Off Game Books.jpg|Japanese used game books sold at Book Off\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Book Off}}\n{{Portal|Companies|Books}}\n* {{official website}}\n* [http://www.bookoffusa.com/ U.S. website]\n\n{{Bookstore Chains}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Bookstores of Japan]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Kanagawa Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1991]]\n[[Category:1991 establishments in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Book Off (\u30d6\u30c3\u30af\u30aa\u30d5\u30b3\u30fc\u30dd\u30ec\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3)\n| logo             = Bookoff Corporation Logo.svg\n| type             = [[Bookstore]]\n| genre            = \n| foundation       = 1991\n| founder          = \n| location_city    = [[Sagamihara, Kanagawa]]\n| location_country = [[Japan]]\n| location         = \n| locations        = \n| area_served      = Worldwide\n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Retail]]\n| products         = Second-hand [[book]]s, [[magazine]]s, [[manga]], [[CD]]s, [[DVD]]s, [[video game]]s, [[video game console]]s, [[mobile phone]]s and [[portable media player]]s\n| services         = \n| market cap       = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = \n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n[[File:Book off.jpg|thumb|Book OFF at Higashiyama, Nara]]\n[[File:Book Off Shibuya.jpg|200px|right|Book Off in the middle of [[Shibuya]]]]\n{{nihongo|'''Book Off'''|\u30d6\u30c3\u30af\u30aa\u30d5\u30b3\u30fc\u30dd\u30ec\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3|Bukku Ofu K\u014dpor\u0113shon}} ({{tyo|3313}}) is [[Japan]]'s largest chain of [[Used goods|used]] [[bookstore]]s. Founded in August 1991, the company has had explosive success, expanding to 866 stores throughout Japan and eight overseas locations (as of August 2006). In addition to books, its chains also sell [[manga]], [[CD]]s, [[DVD]]s, [[video game]]s, and even used [[video game consoles]], [[mobile phone]]s and [[portable media player]]s. The stores are distinguished by their large surface area, cleanliness and bright illumination.\n\n== Operations ==\n\nAs stores are larger it is easier for shoppers to find what they are looking for. Browsing is encouraged, shown with a typical scene of high-school students who read through entire series of [[manga]] standing quietly in the aisles. Another innovation cited for its success is the practice of shaving the edges off the pages of books using a special machine in order to make them appear newer.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | title =Screen savers\n  | newspaper =The Economist\n  | pages =\n  | year =\n  | date =May 24, 2007\n  | url =http://www.economist.com/business/displaystory.cfm?story_id=9231860}}</ref> By offering a wide selection of books that appear like new at reduced prices, Book Off has aggressively targeted conventional bookstore chains, which since 1953<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WSoj5nVrpR0C&pg=PA452|page=452|title=Handbook of Oriental Studies. Section 5 Japan, Modern Japanese Society|isbn=90-04-10516-6|author=J. Kreiner|author2=U. Mvhwald|author3=H. D. Vlschleger|year=2004}}</ref> have been unable to discount new and near-new books and other media due to government regulations which enable a publisher's cartel.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EizYm46Kv_AC&pg=PA390|title=Global Strategy|author=Mike W. Peng|year=2008|isbn=0-324-59099-7|pages=390\u2013393}}</ref>\n\nBook Off is frequently cited as a rare example of a corporation that was able to grow during the so-called \"lost decade\" of [[economic stagnation]] that followed the collapse of the [[Japanese asset price bubble]], through its use of innovative business strategies that are covered in the Japanese business press. It expanded from merely used books to used second-hand merchandise through its Hard Off stores and to the video rental market through Tsutaya.\n\n==International stores==\n\nBook Off also operates several stores in [[United States]], two in [[Seoul]] and two in [[Paris]]<ref>[https://lingonbook.fr/nos-boutiques-bookoff/ Nos Boutiques BOOKOFF]</ref>. In 2012, it closed its only Canadian store in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]. In the USA, there is one store in [[New York (state)|New York]], seven stores in [[California]], and two stores in [[Hawaii]].\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nImage:Book Off Manga.jpg|Thousands of manga volumes at Book Off\nImage:Book-Off! Op\u00e9ra Paris.jpg|Book-Off! store near Op\u00e9ra in [[Paris]]\nImage:Book Off Game Books.jpg|Japanese used game books sold at Book Off\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Book Off}}\n{{Portal|Companies|Books}}\n* {{official website}}\n* [http://www.bookoffusa.com/ U.S. website]\n\n{{Bookstore Chains}}\n\n[[Category:Bookstores of Japan]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Kanagawa Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1991]]\n[[Category:1991 establishments in Japan]]\n", "name_user": "MathXplore", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_Off"}
{"title_page": "Guy Garvey", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Guy Garvey\n| image               = Guy_Garvey_of_Elbow_at_the_V_Festival_2009.jpg\n| caption             = Garvey at the 2009 [[V Festival]], [[Chelmsford]]\n| image_size          =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Guy Edward John Garvey\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1974|3|06|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Bury, Lancashire]], England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| origin              =\n| instrument          = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n* percussion\n* harmonica\n* keyboards\n}}\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]] \n* [[indie rock]]\n* [[art rock]]\n* [[progressive rock]]\n}}\n| occupation          ={{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* producer\n* arranger\n* radio broadcaster\n}}\n| years_active        = 1990\u2013present\n| label               =\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Elbow (band)|Elbow]]\n* [[I Am Kloot]]\n}}\n| website             = {{URL|elbow.co.uk}}\n}}\n'''Guy Edward John Garvey''' (born 6 March 1974)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rateyourmusic.com/artist/guy_garvey|title=Guy Garvey discography|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref> is an English musician, singer, songwriter and [[BBC Radio 6 Music|BBC 6 Music]] presenter. He is the lead singer and lyricist of the [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Elbow (band)|Elbow]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[Garvey]] grew up in [[Bury, Lancashire]] of Irish descent.<ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/top-accolade-for-the-script-1.837653 | title=Top accolade for The Script | quote=My great-great grandfather left Cork in 1822 and the Garveys have been in Manchester ever since | newspaper=[[The Irish Times]] | author=Ronan McGreevy | date=17 March 2009}}</ref> His father spent most of his working life as a newspaper proofreader, later working as a school assistant and his mother was a police officer before becoming a psychologist. One of seven siblings, Garvey has five older sisters: Gina, Louise, Sam, Karen, and Becky. His younger brother is actor Marcus Garvey.<ref name=Guard1015>{{cite news|author=Hattenstone, Simon |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/oct/31/guy-garvey-interview-solo-album-elbow?CMP=fb_gu|title=Guy Garvey: \u2018I used to think booze helped me write. It doesn\u2019t\u2019|newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=31 October 2015|accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Dave Simpson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jul/25/elbow.mercuryprize |title=Guardian profile |newspaper=The Guardian |date= 25 July 2008|accessdate=31 January 2013 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn the early 1990s, while at sixth-form college in [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Whitefield]],<ref>{{cite news |work=Bury Times |date=7 August 2014 |title=Elbow star Guy Garvey tells of band's beginnings in Tottington |url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/11395384.Elbow_star_Guy_Garvey_tells_of_band_s_beginnings_in_Tottington/ |accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref> near Bury, Garvey formed Elbow with Mark and Craig Potter, Pete Turner, and Richard Jupp. He serves as the lyricist of Elbow, and has been widely praised for his songwriting throughout his career. As well as vocal duties Garvey has also played a wide variety of instruments live including both electric and acoustic guitar, trumpet, and various forms of percussion. Elbow won two [[Ivor Novello award]]s for best song writing for the 2008 single \"Grounds for Divorce\" as well as best contemporary song for \"[[One Day Like This (song)|One Day Like This]]\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Rosie Swash |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/may/21/elbow-triumph-ivor-novello-awards |title=Double triumph for Elbow at Ivor Novello awards  |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=28 October 2015}}</ref> He was awarded a lifetime achievement honour by the [[Radio Academy]] in 2014.<ref name=\"radioacademy.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.radioacademy.org/about/honours/ |title=Radio Academy |publisher=Radio Academy |accessdate=28 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901030000/http://www.radioacademy.org/about/honours/ |archivedate=1 September 2015 }}</ref> In the same year, he also featured on the re-launched [[Band Aid 30|Band Aid]] charity's single to raise funds for the [[2014 Ebola crisis|Ebola crisis]] in Africa.<ref name=\"radioacademy.org\"/> Garvey, with Elbow, was commissioned by the [[BBC]] to write the theme song for the [[2012 London Olympics]] and Elbow performed this song, \"First Steps\" at the closing ceremony of the [[Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Elbow Unveils First Steps|url=http://www.nme.com/news/elbow/64657|website=NME}}</ref>\n\nAmongst other work, Garvey produced and recorded the [[I Am Kloot]] album ''[[Natural History (I Am Kloot album)|Natural History]]'' (2001). Alongside Elbow keyboard player [[Craig Potter (musician)|Craig Potter]] he also produced I Am Kloot's single \"[[Maybe I Should]]\" (2005, not associated with any album), their [[Mercury Prize|Mercury Music Prize]] nominated 2010 album ''[[Sky at Night (I Am Kloot album)|Sky at Night]]'' and their 2013 album ''[[Let It All In]]''. Elbow were themselves Mercury Music Prize nominees, in 2011, for the album ''[[Build a Rocket Boys!]]'' and won the prize in 2008 for their album \"[[The Seldom Seen Kid]]\". In addition, Garvey made an appearance on [[Massive Attack]]'s 2010 album record ''[[Heligoland (album)|Heligoland]]''.\n\nHe is a member of the [[British Academy of Songwriters, Composers and Authors]] (BASCA).<ref name=\"UBR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.unsignedbandreview.com/british-academy-of-songwriters-composers-and-authors.html |publisher=The Unsigned band review |title=British Academy of Songwriters, Composers and Authors |author=Founder of UBR |date=18 May 2009 |accessdate=4 February 2012}}</ref> In April 2012 Garvey became a patron of the [http://www.craftanddesign.com/ Manchester Craft and Design Centre]. In recognition of his outstanding contribution to music he received, in July of the same year, an [[honorary degree|honorary doctorate]] from [[Manchester Metropolitan University]], to become a [[Doctor of Arts]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.staff.mmu.ac.uk/manmetlife/news/view/honorary-doctorates-announced |title=Honorary Doctorates announced|publisher=Manchester Metropolitan University|accessdate=31 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202035604/http://www.staff.mmu.ac.uk/manmetlife/news/view/honorary-doctorates-announced |archivedate=2 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nGarvey has been a presenter on [[BBC Radio 6 Music|BBC 6 Music]] since 2007(Sunday afternoon 2&nbsp;pm to 4&nbsp;pm, British time) and previously presented a show on Sunday evenings on [[XFM]]. \nHe had a monthly column in the now-defunct listings magazine ''[[City Life (magazine)|City Life]]'' and is a patron of the [[Mines Advisory Group]] (MAG),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maginternational.org/ |title=The Mines Advisory Group |publisher=Maginternational.org |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref> the [[Manchester]]-based charity responsible for clearing war zones of mines and munitions worldwide.\n\nIn 2015, Garvey presented ''Music Box'', an [[iPlayer]]-exclusive series covering emerging and established bands. Garvey has also read several children's stories for the [[CBeebies]] \"Bedtime Stories\" program on the BBC.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\nIn 2015, Garvey announced that he would be releasing his first solo studio album while continuing his duties as Elbow's lead songwriter. The resulting album, ''[[Courting the Squall]]'', was released on 30 October 2015, by [[Polydor Records]] in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goodacre|first1=Kate|title=Elbow's Guy Garvey is going solo with his new album Courting the Squall|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a668744/elbows-guy-garvey-is-going-solo-with-his-new-album-courting-the-squall.html#~ppSd95v5mffpyb|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Guy Garvey - Courting The Squall|url = http://www.discogs.com/Guy-Garvey-Courting-The-Squall/release/7663178|publisher = discogs|accessdate = 14 November 2015}}</ref> On 27 October 2015 Garvey appeared on [[BBC Two]]'s ''[[Later... with Jools Holland]]'', where he performed \"Angela's Eyes\" and \"Belly of the Whale\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06myydx |title=BBC Two - Later... with Jools Holland, Series 47 Live, Episode 7 |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=27 October 2016 |accessdate=28 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Garvey appeared in the BBC television sitcom ''[[Peter Kay's Car Share]]'', playing Kayleigh's brother-in-law Steve.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p04wytcq/credits |title=BBC Peter Kay's Car Share |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=11 April 2017 |accessdate=11 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGarvey began dating actress [[Rachael Stirling]] in 2015<ref name=Guard1015 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/rachael-stirling-interview-privilege-property-and-the-curse-of-hailing-from-thespian-royalty-a6723566.html|title=The Tipping the Velvet star is returning to our screens in the BBC's Capital|first=Gerard|last=Gilbert|date=7 November 2015|work=The Independent}}</ref> and the two were married in June 2016 at [[Manchester Town Hall]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/guy-garvey-married-rachael-stirling-11448677|title=Guy Garvey has married actress girlfriend Rachael Stirling|last=Walters|first=Sarah|date=2016-06-09|website=men|access-date=2016-06-09}}</ref> The couple had their first child, a son named Jack, in April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/life/rachel-stirling-life-diana-riggs-daughter-whirlwind-romance/|title=Rachel Stirling on life as Diana Rigg's daughter and her whirlwind romance with Elbow's Guy Garvey}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===With Elbow===\n*''[[Asleep in the Back]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Cast of Thousands]]'' (2003)\n*''[[Leaders of the Free World]]'' (2005)\n*''[[The Seldom Seen Kid]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Build a Rocket Boys!]]'' (2011)\n*''[[The Take Off and Landing of Everything]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Little Fictions]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Giants of All Sizes]]'' (2019)\n\n===Solo===\n*''[[Courting the Squall]]'' (2015)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.elbow.co.uk Elbow official website]\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0072q60 ''Guy Garvey's Finest Hour''] (BBC Radio 6 Music)\n\n{{Elbow}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garvey, Guy}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 6 Music presenters]]\n[[Category:British DJs]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:English tenors]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:British columnists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Music in the Metropolitan Borough of Bury]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Manchester]]\n[[Category:People from Bury, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Fiction Records artists]]\n[[Category:English male guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Guy Garvey\n| image               = Guy_Garvey_of_Elbow_at_the_V_Festival_2009.jpg\n| caption             = Garvey at the 2009 [[V Festival]], [[Chelmsford]]\n| image_size          =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Guy Edward John Garvey\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1974|3|06|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Bury, Lancashire]], England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| origin              =\n| instrument          = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n* percussion\n* harmonica\n* keyboards\n}}\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]] \n* [[indie rock]]\n* [[art rock]]\n* [[progressive rock]]\n}}\n| occupation          ={{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* producer\n* arranger\n* radio broadcaster\n}}\n| years_active        = 1990\u2013present\n| label               =\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Elbow (band)|Elbow]]\n* [[I Am Kloot]]\n}}\n| website             = {{URL|elbow.co.uk}}\n}}\n'''Guy Edward John Garvey''' (born 6 March 1974)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rateyourmusic.com/artist/guy_garvey|title=Guy Garvey discography|publisher=|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref> is an English musician, singer, songwriter and [[BBC Radio 6 Music|BBC 6 Music]] presenter. He is the lead singer and lyricist of the [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Elbow (band)|Elbow]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[Garvey]] grew up in [[Bury, Lancashire]] of Irish descent.<ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/top-accolade-for-the-script-1.837653 | title=Top accolade for The Script | quote=My great-great grandfather left Cork in 1822 and the Garveys have been in Manchester ever since | newspaper=[[The Irish Times]] | author=Ronan McGreevy | date=17 March 2009}}</ref> His father spent most of his working life as a newspaper proofreader, later working as a school assistant and his mother was a police officer before becoming a psychologist. One of seven siblings, Garvey has five older sisters: Gina, Louise, Sam, Karen, and Becky. His younger brother is actor Marcus Garvey.<ref name=Guard1015>{{cite news|author=Hattenstone, Simon |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/oct/31/guy-garvey-interview-solo-album-elbow?CMP=fb_gu|title=Guy Garvey: \u2018I used to think booze helped me write. It doesn\u2019t\u2019|newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=31 October 2015|accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Dave Simpson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jul/25/elbow.mercuryprize |title=Guardian profile |newspaper=The Guardian |date= 25 July 2008|accessdate=31 January 2013 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn the early 1990s, while at sixth-form college in [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Whitefield]],<ref>{{cite news |work=Bury Times |date=7 August 2014 |title=Elbow star Guy Garvey tells of band's beginnings in Tottington |url=http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/11395384.Elbow_star_Guy_Garvey_tells_of_band_s_beginnings_in_Tottington/ |accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref> near Bury, Garvey formed Elbow with Mark and Craig Potter, Pete Turner, and Richard Jupp. He serves as the lyricist of Elbow, and has been widely praised for his songwriting throughout his career. As well as vocal duties Garvey has also played a wide variety of instruments live including both electric and acoustic guitar, trumpet, and various forms of percussion. Elbow won two [[Ivor Novello award]]s for best song writing for the 2008 single \"Grounds for Divorce\" as well as best contemporary song for \"[[One Day Like This (song)|One Day Like This]]\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Rosie Swash |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/may/21/elbow-triumph-ivor-novello-awards |title=Double triumph for Elbow at Ivor Novello awards &#124; Music |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=28 October 2015}}</ref> He was awarded a lifetime achievement honour by the [[Radio Academy]] in 2014.<ref name=\"radioacademy.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.radioacademy.org/about/honours/ |title=Radio Academy |publisher=Radio Academy |accessdate=28 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901030000/http://www.radioacademy.org/about/honours/ |archivedate=1 September 2015 }}</ref> In the same year, he also featured on the re-launched [[Band Aid 30|Band Aid]] charity's single to raise funds for the [[2014 Ebola crisis|Ebola crisis]] in Africa.<ref name=\"radioacademy.org\"/> Garvey, with Elbow, was commissioned by the [[BBC]] to write the theme song for the [[2012 London Olympics]] and Elbow performed this song, \"First Steps\" at the closing ceremony of the [[Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Elbow Unveils First Steps|url=http://www.nme.com/news/elbow/64657|website=NME}}</ref>\n\nAmongst other work, Garvey produced and recorded the [[I Am Kloot]] album ''[[Natural History (I Am Kloot album)|Natural History]]'' (2001). Alongside Elbow keyboard player [[Craig Potter (musician)|Craig Potter]] he also produced I Am Kloot's single \"[[Maybe I Should]]\" (2005, not associated with any album), their [[Mercury Prize|Mercury Music Prize]] nominated 2010 album ''[[Sky at Night (I Am Kloot album)|Sky at Night]]'' and their 2013 album ''[[Let It All In]]''. Elbow were themselves Mercury Music Prize nominees, in 2011, for the album ''[[Build a Rocket Boys!]]'' and won the prize in 2008 for their album \"[[The Seldom Seen Kid]]\". In addition, Garvey made an appearance on [[Massive Attack]]'s 2010 album record ''[[Heligoland (album)|Heligoland]]''.\n\nHe is a member of the [[British Academy of Songwriters, Composers and Authors]] (BASCA).<ref name=\"UBR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.unsignedbandreview.com/british-academy-of-songwriters-composers-and-authors.html |publisher=The Unsigned band review |title=British Academy of Songwriters, Composers and Authors |author=Founder of UBR |date=18 May 2009 |accessdate=4 February 2012}}</ref> In April 2012 Garvey became a patron of the [http://www.craftanddesign.com/ Manchester Craft and Design Centre]. In recognition of his outstanding contribution to music he received, in July of the same year, an [[honorary degree|honorary doctorate]] from [[Manchester Metropolitan University]], to become a [[Doctor of Arts]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.staff.mmu.ac.uk/manmetlife/news/view/honorary-doctorates-announced |title=Honorary Doctorates announced &#124; ManMetLife &#124; Manchester Metropolitan University |publisher=Staff.mmu.ac.uk |accessdate=31 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202035604/http://www.staff.mmu.ac.uk/manmetlife/news/view/honorary-doctorates-announced |archivedate=2 December 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nGarvey has been a presenter on [[BBC Radio 6 Music|BBC 6 Music]] since 2007(Sunday afternoon 2&nbsp;pm to 4&nbsp;pm, British time) and previously presented a show on Sunday evenings on [[XFM]]. \nHe had a monthly column in the now-defunct listings magazine ''[[City Life (magazine)|City Life]]'' and is a patron of the [[Mines Advisory Group]] (MAG),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maginternational.org/ |title=The Mines Advisory Group |publisher=Maginternational.org |date= |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref> the [[Manchester]]-based charity responsible for clearing war zones of mines and munitions worldwide.\n\nIn 2015, Garvey presented ''Music Box'', an [[iPlayer]]-exclusive series covering emerging and established bands. Garvey has also read several children's stories for the [[CBeebies]] \"Bedtime Stories\" program on the BBC.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\nIn 2015, Garvey announced that he would be releasing his first solo studio album while continuing his duties as Elbow's lead songwriter. The resulting album, ''[[Courting the Squall]]'', was released on 30 October 2015, by [[Polydor Records]] in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goodacre|first1=Kate|title=Elbow's Guy Garvey is going solo with his new album Courting the Squall|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a668744/elbows-guy-garvey-is-going-solo-with-his-new-album-courting-the-squall.html#~ppSd95v5mffpyb|website=Digital Spy|publisher=Digital Spy|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Guy Garvey - Courting The Squall|url = http://www.discogs.com/Guy-Garvey-Courting-The-Squall/release/7663178|website = Discogs|accessdate = 14 November 2015}}</ref> On 27 October 2015 Garvey appeared on [[BBC Two]]'s ''[[Later... with Jools Holland]]'', where he performed \"Angela's Eyes\" and \"Belly of the Whale\".<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06myydx |title=BBC Two - Later... with Jools Holland, Series 47 Live, Episode 7 |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=27 October 2016 |accessdate=28 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Garvey appeared in the BBC television sitcom ''[[Peter Kay's Car Share]]'', playing Kayleigh's brother-in-law Steve.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p04wytcq/credits |title=BBC Peter Kay's Car Share |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=11 April 2017 |accessdate=11 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGarvey began dating actress [[Rachael Stirling]] in 2015<ref name=Guard1015 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/rachael-stirling-interview-privilege-property-and-the-curse-of-hailing-from-thespian-royalty-a6723566.html|title=The Tipping the Velvet star is returning to our screens in the BBC's Capital|first=Gerard|last=Gilbert|date=7 November 2015|work=The Independent}}</ref> and the two were married in June 2016 at [[Manchester Town Hall]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/guy-garvey-married-rachael-stirling-11448677|title=Guy Garvey has married actress girlfriend Rachael Stirling|last=Walters|first=Sarah|date=2016-06-09|website=men|access-date=2016-06-09}}</ref> The couple had their first child, a son named Jack, in April 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/life/rachel-stirling-life-diana-riggs-daughter-whirlwind-romance/|title=Rachel Stirling on life as Diana Rigg's daughter and her whirlwind romance with Elbow's Guy Garvey|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===With Elbow===\n*''[[Asleep in the Back]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Cast of Thousands]]'' (2003)\n*''[[Leaders of the Free World]]'' (2005)\n*''[[The Seldom Seen Kid]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Build a Rocket Boys!]]'' (2011)\n*''[[The Take Off and Landing of Everything]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Little Fictions]]'' (2017)\n*''[[Giants of All Sizes]]'' (2019)\n\n===Solo===\n*''[[Courting the Squall]]'' (2015)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.elbow.co.uk Elbow official website]\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0072q60 ''Guy Garvey's Finest Hour''] (BBC Radio 6 Music)\n\n{{Elbow}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Garvey, Guy}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 6 Music presenters]]\n[[Category:British DJs]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:English tenors]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:British columnists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Music in the Metropolitan Borough of Bury]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Manchester]]\n[[Category:People from Bury, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Fiction Records artists]]\n[[Category:English male guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "EngvarB,Script-assisted fixes: perCS1andMOS:ITALICS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guy_Garvey"}
{"title_page": "Sarfraz Hussain", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistani politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sarfraz Hussain\n| honorific-suffix = \n| office = Member of the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]]\n| term_start = 15 August 2018\n| term end   =\n|constituency= PP-173 (Lahore-XXX)\t\n|nationality = Pakistani\n|party = [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]]\n}}\n\n'''Sarfraz Hussain''' is a [[Pakistani]] politician who has been a member of the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]] since August 2018.\n\n==Political career==\nHe was elected to the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]] as a candidate of [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]] from Constituency PP-173 (Lahore-XXX) in [[2018 Pakistani general election]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Election Results 2018 - Constituency Details |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/election/constituency/PP-173 |website=www.thenews.com.pk |publisher=The News |accessdate=29 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hussain, Sarfraz}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf MPAs (Punjab)]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pakistani politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sarfraz Hussain\n| honorific-suffix = \n| office = Member of the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]]\n| term_start = 15 August 2018\n| term end   =\n|constituency= PP-173 (Lahore-XXX)\t\n|nationality = Pakistani\n|party = [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]]\n}}\n\n'''Sarfraz Hussain''' is a Pakistani politician who has been a member of the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]] since August 2018.\n\n==Political career==\nHe was elected to the [[Provincial Assembly of the Punjab]] as a candidate of [[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf]] from Constituency PP-173 (Lahore-XXX) in [[2018 Pakistani general election]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Election Results 2018 - Constituency Details |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/election/constituency/PP-173 |website=www.thenews.com.pk |publisher=The News |accessdate=29 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hussain, Sarfraz}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf MPAs (Punjab)]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Audrey A. Wong", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added wiki link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarfraz_Hussain"}
{"title_page": "Casio", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese consumer electronics company}}\n{{distinguish|Casino}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name           = Casio Computer Co., Ltd.<br />{{lang|ja|\u30ab\u30b7\u30aa\u8a08\u7b97\u6a5f\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e}}\n| logo           = Casio logo.svg\n| image          = CASIO-Honsya-Syaoku.jpg\n| image_size     = 250px\n| image_caption  = Casio's world headquarters in [[Shibuya]], Tokyo\n| caption        =\n| type           = [[Public Company|Public]] ([[Kabushiki gaisha|K.K]])\n| traded_as      = {{tyo|6952}}\n| slogan =\n| foundation     = {{start date and age|df=yes|1946|4}} (as Kashio Seisakujo)<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|url=http://world.casio.com/corporate/history/|title=History|accessdate=30 April 2012|publisher=Casio Computer Co., Ltd.}}</ref><br>{{start date|df=yes|1957|6}} (as Casio Computer Co., Ltd.)\n| founder        = Tadao Kashio\n| location       = [[Shibuya]], [[Tokyo]], Japan<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web|url=https://world.casio.com/corporate/profile/?_ga=2.266251786.446284250.1582347473-1747320341.1571484870|title=Company Data|work=Casio|accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n| key_people     = Kazuhiro Kashio {{small|([[President (corporate title)|President]] and [[Chief executive officer|CEO]])}}\n| industry       = [[Consumer electronics]]\n| products       = {{Flatlist|\n* [[Watch]]es\n* [[Clock]]s\n* [[Calculator]]s\n* [[Digital camera]]s\n* [[Electronic musical instrument]]s\n* [[Label printer]]s\n* [[Printer (computing)|Page printers]]\n* [[Personal computer|Office computers]]\n}}\n| operating_income = \u00a522,459 million <small>(2018)</small><ref>{{cite web|title=CASIO Annual Report 2017|url=https://world.casio.com/media/ir/results/201901_772/results63_3rd.pdf|website=CASIO|accessdate=28 February 2019|format=PDF}}</ref>\n| revenue        =  \u00a5314.7 billion <small>(2018)</small><ref>{{cite web|title=CASIO Annual Report 2018|url=http://world.casio.com/media/files/ir/annual/annual_2018.pdf|website=CASIO|accessdate=23 February 2020|format=PDF}}</ref>\n| num_employees  = 11,868 <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"profile\"/>\n| homepage       = [http://world.casio.com/ world.casio.com]\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Casio Computer Co., Ltd.'''|\u30ab\u30b7\u30aa\u8a08\u7b97\u6a5f\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|Kashio Keisanki Kabushiki-gaisha}} is a Japanese  [[Multinational corporation|multinational]] [[consumer electronics]] and commercial electronics manufacturing [[corporation|company]] headquartered in [[Shibuya]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]. Its products include [[calculator]]s, [[mobile phone]]s, [[digital camera]]s, electronic [[musical instrument]]s, and analogue and [[digital watch]]es. It was founded in 1946, and  in 1957 introduced the world's first entirely electric compact calculator. It was an early digital camera innovator, and during the 1980s and 1990s, the company developed numerous affordable home electronic keyboards for musicians along with introducing the world's first mass-produced digital watches.\n\n==History==\nCasio was established as Kashio Seisakujo in April 1946 by Tadao Kashio ([[:ja:\u6a2b\u5c3e\u5fe0\u96c4|\u6a2b\u5c3e\u5fe0\u96c4]] 1917\u20131993), an [[engineer]] specializing in fabrication technology.<ref name=\"History\"/> Kashio's first major product was the yubiwa pipe, a finger ring that would hold a [[cigarette]], allowing the wearer to [[smoking in Japan|smoke]] the cigarette down to its nub while also leaving the wearer's hands-free.<ref name=\"Casio-Europe\">{{cite web|title=CASIO Corporate History 1954 |accessdate=13 February 2016|url=http://www.casio-europe.com/euro/corporate/corporatehistory/detail/1954/|website=CASIO-Europe|publisher=CASIO Europe GmbH|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219065117/http://www.casio-europe.com/euro/corporate/corporatehistory/detail/1954/|archivedate=19 February 2016}}</ref> Japan was [[occupation of Japan|impoverished]] immediately following [[World War II]], so cigarettes were valuable, and the invention was a success.\n\nAfter seeing the electric calculators at the first Business Show in [[Ginza]], Tokyo in 1949, Kashio and his younger brothers (Toshio, Kazuo, and Yukio) used their profits from the yubiwa pipe to develop their calculators. Most of the calculators at that time worked using gears and could be operated by hand using a crank or using a motor (see [[adding machine]]). \n\nToshio possessed some knowledge of electronics and set out to make a calculator using [[solenoid]]s. The desk-sized calculator was finished in 1954 and was Japan's first electro-mechanical calculator. One of the central and more important innovations of the calculator was its adoption of the 10-key number pad; at that time other calculators were using a \"full keypad\", which meant that each place in the number (1s, 10s, 100s, etc ...) had nine keys. Another distinguishing innovation was the use of a single display window instead of the three display windows (one for each argument and one for the answer) used in other calculators.<ref name=\"History\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://astrumpeople.com/tadao-kashio-biography/|title=Tadao Kashio Biography: History of Casio Computer Company|publisher=}}</ref> \n\nCasio Computer Co., Ltd. was formed in June 1957.<ref name=\"History\"/> That year, Casio released the Model 14-A, sold for 485,000 [[Japanese yen|yen]],<ref>[http://www.dentaku-museum.com/calc/calculator/casiod/casiod.html Casio desktop calculator] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080112230255/http://www.dentaku-museum.com/calc/calculator/casiod/casiod.html |date=12 January 2008 }} by Dentaku Museum.</ref> the world's first all-electric compact calculator, which was based on relay technology.\n\nIn the 1980s, Casio's budget electronic instruments and its line of affordable home electronic [[Keyboard instrument|musical keyboard instruments]] became popular. The company also became well known for the wide variety and innovation of its [[wristwatch]]es. It was one of the earliest manufacturers of [[quartz watch]]es, both digital and analog. It also began selling calculator watches during this time. Casio also introduced one of the first watches that could display the time in many different time zones of the world and with features like recording temperature, atmospheric-pressure and altitude. In the later years, Casio's wristwatches were fitted with receivers to synchronise with radio towers around the world and [[Global Positioning System]] for timekeeping accuracy.\n\nA number of notable digital camera innovations have also been made by Casio, including the QV-10, the first consumer digital camera with an LCD screen on the back<ref name=\"Casio\"/> (developed by a team led by Hiroyuki Suetaka in 1995), the first consumer three-megapixel camera, the first true ultra-compact model, and the first digital camera to incorporate ceramic lens technology, using [[Lumicera]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dpreview.com/articles/7434120861/casioceramiclens|title=Casio's ceramic lens|website=DPReview}}</ref>\n\n=== Price fixing ===\n\nIn July 2019, the company's UK arm, '''Casio Electronics Co. Ltd ''', was fined \u00a33.7million after admitting [[resale price maintenance]] (a form of [[price-fixing]]) between 2013 and  2018, in breach of the United Kingdom's [[Competition Act 1998]].<ref name=\"Kollewe\">{{cite news |last1=Kollewe |first1=Julia |title=Guitar maker Fender fined \u00a34.5m for price fixing in UK |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/jan/22/guitar-maker-fender-fined-45m-for-price-fixing-in-uk |accessdate=22 January 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=22 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"cmA\">{{cite web |title=Piano supplier fined \u00a33.7m for illegally preventing price discounts |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/piano-supplier-fined-3-7m-for-illegally-preventing-price-discounts |publisher=[[Competition and Markets Authority]] |accessdate=22 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nCasio's products include [[watch]]es, [[calculator]]s, [[electronic keyboard]]s and other digital products such as [[Digital photography|digital camera]]s ([[Exilim]] series), [[film camera]]s, [[cash register]]s, [[laptop]]s and [[sub-notebook]] computers, [[mobile phone]]s, [[Personal digital assistant|PDAs]] (E-Data Bank), [[Electronic dictionary|electronic dictionaries]], [[Casio digital diary|digital diaries]] (early PDAs), [[Handheld electronic game|electronic games]], [[computer printer]]s, [[clock]]s, and [[Handheld television|portable televisions]].\n\nIn the 1970s and 80s, Casio was best known for its electronic (including scientific) calculators, electronic musical instruments and affordable digital watches incorporating innovative technology. Today, Casio is most commonly known for making durable and reliable electronic products.<ref name=\"Casio\">Review: [http://www.casio-intl.com/asia-mea/en/calc/history/ Casio:History]</ref> The [[G-Shock]] range of shock-resistant watches is also very popular, with the original 1983 G-Shock DW-5000C being highly sought-after by collectors. The scientific calculators made by Casio especially the CLASSWIZ series of calculators are known for being affordable while incorporating a host of functions as compared to their competitors.<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://mathclasscalculator.com/index.php/calculators/scientific/casio-classwiz-fx-991ex-full-review/|title=Casio CLASSWIZ FX-991EX Full Review|access-date=25 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nCasio also makes products for local markets, including \"Prayer Compass\" watch series designed to help Muslims pray on time and in the right direction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.casio-intl.com/asia-mea/en/wat/prayercompass/|title=PRAYER COMPASS|publisher=Casio|accessdate=22 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316155733/http://www.casio-intl.com/asia-mea/en/wat/prayercompass/|archive-date=16 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Calculators===\n\n====Scientific calculators====\n[[File:Fx-991EX.jpg|thumb|Casio fx-991EX \"CLASSWIZ\" scientific calculator]]\nCasio calculators include:\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* [[Casio graphic calculators|Graphing]]\n** [[Casio 9860 series|FX-9860G / GII / SD]]\n** [[Casio 9860 series|FX-9860G Slim]]\n** [[ClassPad 300]] Plus / 330\n** [[Casio ClassPad 300#fx-CP400|ClassPad II fx-CP400]]\n** fx-CG10 / 20 / 50\n** fx-CG500\n** Algebra FX 2.0 Plus\n** FX 1.0 Plus\n** CFX-9850GC Plus\n** CFX-9850GB Plus\n** CFX-9800G\n** fx-9750G Plus / GII\n** fx-8500G, 8000G\n** fx-7500G, 7400G Plus / GII\n** [[Casio fx-7000G|fx-7000G]] ''(ca. 1985)''\n** VI-9850GB Plus\n** RM 7000/9000\n* Programming\n** fx-5800P, 3950P, [[Casio fx-3650P|fx-3650P]], 50F Plus ''(2000s)''\n** fx-4500PA, 4500P\n** fx-5500LA, 5500L\n** [[Casio FX-3900PV|fx-3900PV]], 3900P ''(1990s)''\n** fx-4800P \n** fx-3600P ''(1980s)''\n** fx-4000P, 3500P, 3800P, fx-5000F, 50F  ''(late 1980s)''\n** [[Casio FX-850P|FX-850P]]\n** [[Casio FX-702P|FX-702P]] ''(ca. 1981)''\n** [[Casio FX-603P|FX-603P]], [[Casio FX-602P|FX-602P]] ''(1981)''\n** fx-180P, 390PV (Program) ''(early 1980s)'', fx-180PV,\n** FX-502P, 501P ''(ca. 1979)''\n* Professional\n** fx-FD10 Pro ''(2014)'' (Surveying calculator for civil engineering)\n* V.P.A.M. (See: ''[[Casio V.P.A.M. calculators]]'')\n** CLASSWIZ (High-resolution Natural Textbook Display)\n** \"Natural V.P.A.M.\"\n** \"Natural Display\"\n** S-V.P.A.M. / Two-line, Multi-replay\n* LCD (One-line)\n** fx-65 (True fraction) ''(mid 1990s)''\n** fx-95 (equation) ''(mid 1990s)''\n** fx-991D, 570D, 115D, 100D ''(early-mid 1990s)''\n** fx-82D, 250D, 82LB, 82SUPER, 82SX, 82SOLAR ''(early 1990s)''\n** fx-992V, 992VB, 991V, 115V, 85V; fx-991H, 911H ''(early 1990s)''\n** fx-991N, 911N, 115N, 85N; fx-250C, fx-570C ''(late 1980s)''\n** fx-991M, 115M, 85M; fx-451M,''(mid-late 1980s)''\n** fx-650M; fx-580; fx-100C, 82C ''(mid-late 1980s)''\n** fx-570, 100, 350, 77 ''(early-mid 1980s)''\n** fx-82, 82B, 82L, fx-58 ''(early 1980s)''\n** fx-2000, 2200, 2500, fx-48''(late 1970s)''\n* [[vacuum fluorescent display|VFD]] (Digitron) display\n** fx-1, 2, 3 (desk); fx-10 (handheld) ''(early-mid 1970s)'', used MSI (medium scale integration)\n** fx-11, 15, 20, 101, 17, 19, 102, 1000, PRO fx-1, PRO-101, ''(mid-1970s)''\n** fx-21, 29, 31, 39, 120, 140  ''(mid-late 1970s)''\n** fx-201P, 202P (Program) ''(mid 1970s)''\n{{div col end}}\n\n====Basic calculators====\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* LCD display\n** Desk calculators\n*** DS-3TS, DH-160, DV-220, DJ-240D, DJ-120D, MJ-120D, MW-8V ''(2000s)''\n** Pocket calculators\n*** JS-140TVS, NJ-120D, SL-1000TW, HL-122TV ''(2000s)''\n*** HL-810 ''(1985)''\n*** SL-800 (FILM CARD) ''(1983)''\n*** LC-78 (MINI-CARD) ''(1978)''\n** Printing calculators\n*** HR-100TM, DR-210TM ''(2000s)''\n* VFD (Digitron) / LED display\n** Desktop calculators\n*** AL-1000 ''(1967)'' \n** Pocket calculators (1970s)\n*** CM-601 (MINI)\n*** CM-606 (Personal MINI)\n*** 101-MR\n*** Y-811 (Memory-8R)\n*** AL-8 (with fraction input)\n*** H-813 (Personal M-1)\n*** CQ-1 (with clock function)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Watches===\n[[File:Casio G-Shock Master of G Rangeman GW-9400J-1JF.jpg|thumb|\nCasio G-Shock Rangeman watch]]\nCasio watches include:\n* [[G-Shock]]\n** [[Master of G]]\n** Baby-G\n** MT-G\n* Lineage\n* [[Casio Oceanus|Oceanus]]\n* [[Casio Edifice|Edifice]]\n* [[Casio Wave Ceptor|Wave Ceptor]]\n* [[Casio Databank|Databank]]\n* Sheen\n* Youth Series<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.casio-intl.com/in/en/wat/youth/youth-digital/|title=YOUTH DIGITAL &#124; YOUTH SERIES &#124; Timepieces &#124; CASIO|website=CASIO Official Website}}</ref>\n** Classic\n***  W-96H\n***  W-210H\n***  W-213H\n***  W-216H\n***  W-218H\n***  W-800H\n***  HDD-600G\n***  F-200W\n** World time\n***  AE-500W\n*** [[Casio AE-1000W|AE-1000W]]\n***  AE-1100W\n***  AE-1200WH\n***  AE-1400WH\n***  AE-2000W\n***  AE-2100W\n***  AE-3000W\n** Multiple timers\n***  AE-1300W\n** Stopwatch lap memory\n***  W-734\n** Vibration alarm\n*** 