{"title_page": "Nigeria's Got Talent", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian reality television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Nigeria's Got Talent\n| image                    = \n| genre                    = [[Reality television|Reality]]\n| creator                  = [[Simon Cowell]] (''Got Talent'' franchise)\n| presenter                = [[Andre Blaze]]\n| judges                   = [[Dan Foster (DJ)|Dan Foster]]<br>[[Kate Henshaw]]<br> [[Yibo Koko]]\n| country                  = Nigeria<br>United Kingdom\n| language                 = English, [[Nigerian Pidgin]]\n| num_series               = 3\n| num_episodes             = \n| list_episodes            = \n| producer                 = \n| location                 = Various (auditions)<br>[[Lagos]]\n| runtime                  = \n| company                  = \n| distributor              = \n| channel                  = [[Africa Independent Television|AIT]], [[Nigerian Television Authority]]\n| picture_format           = \n| first_aired              = September 16, 2012\n| last_aired               = \n| related                  = \n| website                  = https://web.archive.org/web/20141220054048/http://www.nigeriasgottalent.com/\n| website_title            = Official website\n}}\n\n'''''Nigeria's Got Talent''''' is a [[Nigeria]]n reality talent show which is part of the ''[[Got Talent]]'' franchise. It was launched in 2012 on television stations [[African Independent Television|AIT]] and [[Nigerian Television Authority|NTA]], and sponsored by [[telecommunication]] company Airtel.<ref>[http://www.vanguardngr.com/2012/06/nigeria-got-talent-debuts/ Nigeria's Got Talent Debuts]</ref>\n\nHosted by Andre blaze former presenter on ''Nigeria's Got Talent's'' fore-runner ''The Peak Talent Show'',<ref>[http://thenetng.com/2012/09/why-i-left-nigezie-host-of-nigerias-got-talent-andre-blaze-reveals/ Host of NGT]</ref> the judges are actress [[Kate Henshaw]], comedian Yibo Koko, and radio presenter [[Dan Foster (DJ)|Dan Foster]], who had previously held a similar position on ''[[Idols West Africa]]''.<ref>[http://www.vanguardngr.com/2012/09/kate-henshaw-dan-foster-and-koko-named-judges-for-nigeria-got-talent-show/ Kate Henshaw, Dan Foster and Koko named judges for Nigeria Got Talent show]</ref>\n\nThe current champions are dancing duo Robots for Christ.<ref>[http://www.premiumtimesng.com/arts-entertainment/154907-robots-christ-wins-nigerias-got-talent-season-2.html Robots for Christ wins Nigeria\u2019s Got Talent Season 2]</ref>\n\n==Format==\nThe auditions take place in front of the judges and a live audience in different Nigerian [[City|cities]]. As the contestant performs, each judge may show their disapproval by pressing a buzzer which lights a red 'X' near above the stage. If all three buzzers are pressed, the act ends immediately. To advance to the second round, auditionees must receive at least two 'yes's' or the competition ends for them. After the auditions the judges have to whittle successful acts down to fifty, and all performers are called back to discover if they have progressed to the next round.\n\nThe remaining acts from across the country perform at the live semi-finals, with the two most popular acts from each semi-finals winning a position in the final, and judges may still end a performance early with all three 'X's' buzzed. After the acts have performed, phone lines open and the voting process begins, after which the [[vote]]s are counted and the act with the highest number of public votes is automatically placed in the final. The judges then choose between the second and third most popular acts, with the winner of the most votes automatically gaining a place in the final where the winner of ''Nigeria's Got Talent'' is chosen once again by the public vote and will receive 10 million dollars \n\nThroughout the whole competition, the judges express their views on each act's performance.\n\nThere is no golden buzzer is this version so all act must make though If they receive two yes and say if the progressed to the semi finals and they can't automatically go through to the semi-finals\n\n==Season 1==\n\nAuditions were held in [[Abuja]], [[Calabar]], [[Benin City|Benin]], [[Port Harcourt]], [[Ibadan]], [[Enugu]], and [[Lagos]] where the grand finale was held.<ref>[http://nationalmirroronline.net/new/more-tear-inducing-acts-as-nigerias-got-talent-hits-other-cities/ More tear-inducing acts as Nigeria\u2019s Got Talent hits other cities]</ref> As with the [[Britain's Got Talent|British]] and [[America's Got Talent|American]] versions of the show, applicants were invited to upload video performances onto the show's website which were viewed by producers, and outstanding contestants were called to perform in front of the judges at the main auditions.<ref>[http://www.gottalentnigeria.com/video_auditions.php Video Audition]</ref>\n\nThe top ten finalists were:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Act !! Occupation !! Audition city !! Position <ref>[http://thenetng.com/2012/12/video-meet-the-10-nigerias-got-talent-finalists/ Finalists]</ref>\n|-\n| [[Amarachi|Amarachi Uyanne]] || Dancer/Violinist || Pupil || Benin || Winner\n|-\n| Boniface Ukeme || Dancer || Student || Port Harcourt  || \n|-\n| Chuka Solace || Rapper || Student || Lagos ||\n|-\n| Dr. Bariyu || [[Ventriloquist]] || Medical doctor || Lagos ||\n|-\n| Godwin Stringz || [[Violin]]ist || Student || Benin || First runner up\n|-\n| Impulse || [[Acapella]] group || Students || Port Harcourt ||\n|-\n| DJ Mouth || [[Beat box]]er || Student || Port Harcourt ||\n|-\n| Jesse and ED || [[Ballet]] duo || Pupils || Benin ||\n|-\n| Toke || singer || Pupil || Ibadan ||\n|-\n| Xpendables || [[Street dance]] group || Students|| Port Harcourt ||  \n|}\n\n==Season 2==\n2 Second series of the show was aired on November 8, 2013, with all three judges returning. After rigorous auditions across the cities in Nigeria, this concludes on February 8, 2014 with Robots for Christ winning the second season. The highlights of the finale was posted to YouTube on February 9, 2014.\n\n==Criticism==\nAlthough Henshaw has been promoted as the show's mean judge \u00e1 la [[Simon Cowell]], she has been criticised for going too far. At Season Two's [[Port Harcourt]] auditions, she interrupted a singer credited as Heaven by stating, \"There is no heaven here. Stop singing and get off the stage, or else  I will leave to call your father as the judge\".<ref>[http://telegraphng.com/2013/11/kate-henshaw-dan-foster-walk-nigerias-got-talent/ Kate Henshaw, Dan Foster walk out of Nigeria\u2019s Got Talent]</ref><ref>[http://www.tribune.com.ng/news2013/index.php/en/component/k2/item/27473-nigeria%E2%80%99s-got-talent-kate-henshaw,-dan-foster-walk-out-on-contestant,-viewers.html Nigeria\u2019s Got Talent: Kate Henshaw, Dan Foster walk out on contestant, viewers]</ref><ref>[http://www.vanguardngr.com/2013/11/awful-performance-irritates-airtels-ngt-judges/ Awful Performance Irritates NGT Judges]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Got Talent}}\n\n[[Category:2012 Nigerian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Got Talent]]\n[[Category:Nigerian reality television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Fremantle (company)]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Non-British television series based on British television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nigerian reality television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name      = Nigeria's Got Talent\n| image          = \n| genre          = [[Reality television|Reality]]\n| creator        = [[Simon Cowell]] (''Got Talent'' franchise)\n| presenter     = [[Andre Blaze]] \n| judges         = [[Dan Foster (DJ)|Dan Foster]]<br>[[Kate Henshaw]]<br> [[Yibo Koko]]\n| country        = Nigeria<br>United Kingdom\n| language       = English, [[Nigerian Pidgin]]\n| num_series     = 2\n| num_episodes   = \n| list_episodes  = \n| producer       = \n| location 